text.section:
The county commissioners may adopt an animal control ordinance to:
Create a quasi-judicial deliberative animal control authority for the county to:
Hold public hearings to decide citations, complaints, and other controversies arising under the animal control ordinance, other than those filed with the District Court, subject to the right of a party to file a petition for judicial review in the circuit court; and
Adopt rules and regulations for the governance of its hearings;
Designate an appropriate private agency or department of county government to:
Enforce the provisions of the ordinance;
Maintain records regarding the licensing, impoundment, and disposition of animals coming into the custody of the private agency or department of county government; and
Enter into contracts or agreements to provide for the disposal of animals;
Provide for the designation of animal control shelters in the county;
Specify rules and regulations that may include:
The licensing of dogs, kennels, and pet shops;
The control of rabid animals; and
The disposition of uncontrolled, vicious, and sick animals; and
Provide that a violation of the animal control ordinance is a misdemeanor punishable by imprisonment of up to 30 days or a fine of $1,000, or both for each offense.

The citation shall contain:
The name and address of the person charged;
The nature of the violation;
The location and time of the violation;
The amount of the fine;
The manner, location, and time in which the fine may be paid; and
The cited person's right to elect to stand trial for the violation.
